<TITLE> UK students feeling lucky, could study gambling </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, July 31 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British teenagers could learn about gambling addiction as teachers try to make course material more relevant to a society hooked on betting. The addictive appeal of gambling and how to break free from its hold have been proposed as a topic for the psychology A-level course taken by high-school students in their final two years, the exam board OCR said. Students will have no shortage of real-life examples in Britain, where more than half of adults gamble every week, according to 2006 figures from the country's official Gambling Commission. "With plans for the UK's first super casino being reviewed by the government, the danger of gambling addiction is very topical for students to cover as part of their A-level psychology course," Diane Cole, psychology subject officer for OCR, said. If approved by the government's exam regulators, the gambling curriculum could be taught from September 2008. It would be based on a study by Mark Griffiths, professor of gambling studies at Nottingham Trent University, who has examined such issues as why inveterate gamblers talk aloud to slot machines. "I am delighted that the study of gambling and gambling addiction has found its way onto the core A-level psychology syllabus," Griffiths said. "Against a backdrop of gambling liberalisation and deregulation, gambling addiction looks set to increase and educating students about gambling behaviour will be of real interest." The Responsibility in Gambling Trust, an independent charity that works to combat problem gambling, also welcomed the course. Malcolm Bruce, director of the trust, said most gamblers behave sensibly but some develop addictions "with devastating consequences for themselves, their families and their friends". "We need to know more about how and why gambling affects people in different ways," he said. "At the same time we need to educate people about the potential risks involved in gambli
